™—ЩWarchive/external_nushell_repo_backup/nushell.github.io/book/stdout_stderr_exit_codes.mdЩ@8a96cefe9d94b0116965c9c87051fdfe6c1860dae9af0a001dc94fb05e41bb11ѕStdout, Stderr, and Exit Codes‘ѕStdout, Stderr, and Exit CodesЩ»An important piece of interop between Nushell and external commands is working with the standard streams of data coming from the external.
The first of these important streams is stdout.
’ђђЪTitle: Stdout, Stderr, and Exit Codes
Path: Stdout, Stderr, and Exit Codes
Content:
An important piece of interop between Nushell and external commands is working with the standard streams of data coming from the external.
The first of these important streams is stdout.
—ЩWarchive/external_nushell_repo_backup/nushell.github.io/book/stdout_stderr_exit_codes.mdЩ@fe37d8a32c350a9bde9851a726b1d9d64d20d95cab22540a992a5e62a50e28deѕStdout, Stderr, and Exit Codes‘¦StdoutЪjStdout is the way that most external apps will send data into the pipeline or to the screen. Data sent by an external app to its stdout is received by Nushell by default if it's part of a pipeline:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
external | str join

```
The above would call the external named 
``external``
 and would redirect the stdout output stream into the pipeline. With this redirection, Nushell can then pass the data to the next command in the pipeline, here 
[link: /commands/docs/str_join.md] ``str join``
.
Without the pipeline, Nushell will not do any redirection, allowing it to print directly to the screen.
’ђђЪ¦Title: Stdout, Stderr, and Exit Codes
Path: Stdout
Content:
Stdout is the way that most external apps will send data into the pipeline or to the screen. Data sent by an external app to its stdout is received by Nushell by default if it's part of a pipeline:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
external | str join

```
The above would call the external named 
``external``
 and would redirect the stdout output stream into the pipeline. With this redirection, Nushell can then pass the data to the next command in the pipeline, here 
[link: /commands/docs/str_join.md] ``str join``
.
Without the pipeline, Nushell will not do any redirection, allowing it to print directly to the screen.
—ЩWarchive/external_nushell_repo_backup/nushell.github.io/book/stdout_stderr_exit_codes.mdЩ@68cc529f8a81a498bf743d0f53abe6054cc1f1341ad6904390bc5fb78a7e929fѕStdout, Stderr, and Exit Codes‘¦StderrЪ­Another common stream that external applications often use to print error messages is stderr. By default, Nushell does not do any redirection of stderr, which means that by default it will print to the screen.
But you can pass stderr to a command or a file if you want to:
use 
``e>|``
 to pass stderr to next command.
use 
``e> file``
 to redirect stderr to a file.
use 
``do -i { cmd } | complete``
 to capture stderr message.
’ђђЪйTitle: Stdout, Stderr, and Exit Codes
Path: Stderr
Content:
Another common stream that external applications often use to print error messages is stderr. By default, Nushell does not do any redirection of stderr, which means that by default it will print to the screen.
But you can pass stderr to a command or a file if you want to:
use 
``e>|``
 to pass stderr to next command.
use 
``e> file``
 to redirect stderr to a file.
use 
``do -i { cmd } | complete``
 to capture stderr message.
—ЩWarchive/external_nushell_repo_backup/nushell.github.io/book/stdout_stderr_exit_codes.mdЩ@cc624bdd766bfb9eec51fa523d550766e4911babd17e65d9244a3d56c5e400f8ѕStdout, Stderr, and Exit Codes‘©Exit CodeЪєFinally, external commands have an "exit code". These codes help give a hint to the caller whether the command ran successfully.
Nushell tracks the last exit code of the recently completed external in one of two ways. The first way is with the 
``LAST_EXIT_CODE``
 environment variable.
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
do { external }
$env.LAST_EXIT_CODE

```
The second way is to use the 
[link: /commands/docs/complete.md] ``complete``
 command.
’ђђЪщTitle: Stdout, Stderr, and Exit Codes
Path: Exit Code
Content:
Finally, external commands have an "exit code". These codes help give a hint to the caller whether the command ran successfully.
Nushell tracks the last exit code of the recently completed external in one of two ways. The first way is with the 
``LAST_EXIT_CODE``
 environment variable.
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
do { external }
$env.LAST_EXIT_CODE

```
The second way is to use the 
[link: /commands/docs/complete.md] ``complete``
 command.
—ЩWarchive/external_nushell_repo_backup/nushell.github.io/book/stdout_stderr_exit_codes.mdЩ@223f3c478858a82b9518d66ecc5b189086fc2e8de2b0e663c6818691a93a255bѕStdout, Stderr, and Exit Codes‘Ё commandЪ[link: /commands/docs/complete.md] ``complete``
The 
[link: /commands/docs/complete.md] ``complete``
 command allows you to run an external to completion, and gather the stdout, stderr, and exit code together in one record.
If we try to run the external 
``cat``
 on a file that doesn't exist, we can see what 
[link: /commands/docs/complete.md] ``complete``
 does with the streams, including the redirected stderr:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
cat unknown.txt | complete
# => в•­в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”¬в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв•®
# => в”‚ stdout    в”‚                                             в”‚
# => в”‚ stderr    в”‚ cat: unknown.txt: No such file or directory в”‚
# => в”‚ exit_code в”‚ 1                                           в”‚
# => в•°в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”ґв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв•Ї

```
’ђђЪ[Title: Stdout, Stderr, and Exit Codes
Path:  command
Content:
[link: /commands/docs/complete.md] ``complete``
The 
[link: /commands/docs/complete.md] ``complete``
 command allows you to run an external to completion, and gather the stdout, stderr, and exit code together in one record.
If we try to run the external 
``cat``
 on a file that doesn't exist, we can see what 
[link: /commands/docs/complete.md] ``complete``
 does with the streams, including the redirected stderr:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
cat unknown.txt | complete
# => в•­в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”¬в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв•®
# => в”‚ stdout    в”‚                                             в”‚
# => в”‚ stderr    в”‚ cat: unknown.txt: No such file or directory в”‚
# => в”‚ exit_code в”‚ 1                                           в”‚
# => в•°в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”ґв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв•Ї

```
—ЩWarchive/external_nushell_repo_backup/nushell.github.io/book/stdout_stderr_exit_codes.mdЩ@dc6a957d0eef63dc1a78754856fc2caf3d962a2d38eeef322353d8fccd541db1ѕStdout, Stderr, and Exit Codes‘© commandsЪ``echo``
``print``
``log``
The 
[link: /commands/docs/echo.md] ``echo``
 command is mainly for 
pipes
. It returns its arguments, ignoring the piped-in value. There is usually little reason to use this over just writing the values as-is.
In contrast, the 
[link: /commands/docs/print.md] ``print``
 command prints the given values to stdout as plain text. It can be used to write to standard error output, as well. Unlike 
[link: /commands/docs/echo.md] ``echo``
, this command does not return any value (
``print | describe``
 will return "nothing"). Since this command has no output, there is no point in piping it with other commands.
The 
[link: /book/standard_library.md] standard library
 has commands to write out messages in different logging levels. For example:
@
[link: @snippets/book/std_log.nu] code
Log message examples
The log level for output can be set with the 
[link: /book/special_variables.md#env-nu-log-level] ``NU_LOG_LEVEL``
 environment variable:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
NU_LOG_LEVEL=DEBUG nu std_log.nu

```
’ђђЪKTitle: Stdout, Stderr, and Exit Codes
Path:  commands
Content:
``echo``
``print``
``log``
The 
[link: /commands/docs/echo.md] ``echo``
 command is mainly for 
pipes
. It returns its arguments, ignoring the piped-in value. There is usually little reason to use this over just writing the values as-is.
In contrast, the 
[link: /commands/docs/print.md] ``print``
 command prints the given values to stdout as plain text. It can be used to write to standard error output, as well. Unlike 
[link: /commands/docs/echo.md] ``echo``
, this command does not return any value (
``print | describe``
 will return "nothing"). Since this command has no output, there is no point in piping it with other commands.
The 
[link: /book/standard_library.md] standard library
 has commands to write out messages in different logging levels. For example:
@
[link: @snippets/book/std_log.nu] code
Log message examples
The log level for output can be set with the 
[link: /book/special_variables.md#env-nu-log-level] ``NU_LOG_LEVEL``
 environment variable:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
NU_LOG_LEVEL=DEBUG nu std_log.nu

```
—ЩWarchive/external_nushell_repo_backup/nushell.github.io/book/stdout_stderr_exit_codes.mdЩ@a23619273aa817b41a34e13a85e27fc8616e927cc5688509c567084fc94721efѕStdout, Stderr, and Exit Codes‘±File RedirectionsЪШIf you want to redirect stdout of an external command to a file, you can use 
``out>``
 followed by a file path. Similarly, you can use 
``err>``
 to redirect stderr:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
cat unknown.txt out> out.log err> err.log

```
If you want to redirect both stdout and stderr to the same file, you can use 
``out+err>``
:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
cat unknown.txt out+err> log.log

```
Note that 
``out``
 can be shortened to just 
``o``
, and 
``err``
 can be shortened to just 
``e``
. So, the following examples are equivalent to the previous ones above:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
cat unknown.txt o> out.log e> err.log

cat unknown.txt o+e> log.log

```
Also, any expression can be used for the file path, as long as it is a string value:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
use std
cat unknown.txt o+e> (std null-device)

```
Note that file redirections are scoped to an expression and apply to all external commands in the expression. In the example below, 
``out.txt``
 will contain 
``hello\nworld``
:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
let text = "hello\nworld"
($text | head -n 1; $text | tail -n 1) o> out.txt

```
Pipes and additional file redirections inside the expression will override any file redirections applied from the outside.
’ђђЪTitle: Stdout, Stderr, and Exit Codes
Path: File Redirections
Content:
If you want to redirect stdout of an external command to a file, you can use 
``out>``
 followed by a file path. Similarly, you can use 
``err>``
 to redirect stderr:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
cat unknown.txt out> out.log err> err.log

```
If you want to redirect both stdout and stderr to the same file, you can use 
``out+err>``
:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
cat unknown.txt out+err> log.log

```
Note that 
``out``
 can be shortened to just 
``o``
, and 
``err``
 can be shortened to just 
``e``
. So, the following examples are equivalent to the previous ones above:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
cat unknown.txt o> out.log e> err.log

cat unknown.txt o+e> log.log

```
Also, any expression can be used for the file path, as long as it is a string value:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
use std
cat unknown.txt o+e> (std null-device)

```
Note that file redirections are scoped to an expression and apply to all external commands in the expression. In the example below, 
``out.txt``
 will contain 
``hello\nworld``
:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
let text = "hello\nworld"
($text | head -n 1; $text | tail -n 1) o> out.txt

```
Pipes and additional file redirections inside the expression will override any file redirections applied from the outside.
—ЩWarchive/external_nushell_repo_backup/nushell.github.io/book/stdout_stderr_exit_codes.mdЩ@30d1d896325c7caa9086853a36d907248459d0d6bbce108ef8a9a7d80a27baf3ѕStdout, Stderr, and Exit Codes‘±Pipe RedirectionsЪ1If a regular pipe 
``|``
 comes after an external command, it redirects the stdout of the external command as input to the next command. To instead redirect the stderr of the external command, you can use the stderr pipe, 
``err>|``
 or 
``e>|``
:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
cat unknown.txt e>| str upcase

```
Of course, there is a corresponding pipe for combined stdout and stderr, 
``out+err>|``
 or 
``o+e>|``
:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
nu -c 'print output; print -e error' o+e>| str upcase

```
Unlike file redirections, pipe redirections do not apply to all commands inside an expression. Rather, only the last command in the expression is affected. For example, only 
``cmd2``
 in the snippet below will have its stdout and stderr redirected by the pipe.
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
(cmd1; cmd2) o+e>| cmd3

```
’ђђЪxTitle: Stdout, Stderr, and Exit Codes
Path: Pipe Redirections
Content:
If a regular pipe 
``|``
 comes after an external command, it redirects the stdout of the external command as input to the next command. To instead redirect the stderr of the external command, you can use the stderr pipe, 
``err>|``
 or 
``e>|``
:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
cat unknown.txt e>| str upcase

```
Of course, there is a corresponding pipe for combined stdout and stderr, 
``out+err>|``
 or 
``o+e>|``
:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
nu -c 'print output; print -e error' o+e>| str upcase

```
Unlike file redirections, pipe redirections do not apply to all commands inside an expression. Rather, only the last command in the expression is affected. For example, only 
``cmd2``
 in the snippet below will have its stdout and stderr redirected by the pipe.
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
(cmd1; cmd2) o+e>| cmd3

```
—ЩWarchive/external_nushell_repo_backup/nushell.github.io/book/stdout_stderr_exit_codes.mdЩ@efa7daeec961cbac96bb41a0e0e8d73e253947107d58a7acd5cbca20628ff80eѕStdout, Stderr, and Exit Codes‘«Raw StreamsЪCBoth stdout and stderr are represented as "raw streams" inside of Nushell. These are streams of bytes rather than the structured data used by internal Nushell commands.
Because streams of bytes can be difficult to work with, especially given how common it is to use output as if it was text data, Nushell attempts to convert raw streams into text data. This allows other commands to pull on the output of external commands and receive strings they can further process.
Nushell attempts to convert to text using UTF-8. If at any time the conversion fails, the rest of the stream is assumed to always be bytes.
If you want more control over the decoding of the byte stream, you can use the 
[link: /commands/docs/decode.md] ``decode``
 command. The 
[link: /commands/docs/decode.md] ``decode``
 command can be inserted into the pipeline after the external, or other raw stream-creating command, and will handle decoding the bytes based on the argument you give decode. For example, you could decode shift-jis text this way:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
0x[8a 4c] | decode shift-jis
# => иІќ

```
’ђђЪ„Title: Stdout, Stderr, and Exit Codes
Path: Raw Streams
Content:
Both stdout and stderr are represented as "raw streams" inside of Nushell. These are streams of bytes rather than the structured data used by internal Nushell commands.
Because streams of bytes can be difficult to work with, especially given how common it is to use output as if it was text data, Nushell attempts to convert raw streams into text data. This allows other commands to pull on the output of external commands and receive strings they can further process.
Nushell attempts to convert to text using UTF-8. If at any time the conversion fails, the rest of the stream is assumed to always be bytes.
If you want more control over the decoding of the byte stream, you can use the 
[link: /commands/docs/decode.md] ``decode``
 command. The 
[link: /commands/docs/decode.md] ``decode``
 command can be inserted into the pipeline after the external, or other raw stream-creating command, and will handle decoding the bytes based on the argument you give decode. For example, you could decode shift-jis text this way:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
0x[8a 4c] | decode shift-jis
# => иІќ

```
